---
description: "BusDK Design Document Reference"
alwaysApply: true
globs: ["*"]
---

The canonical BusDK design document is published at https://docs.busdk.com/ and 
must be used as the primary reference for architecture, data formats, CLI 
conventions, module responsibilities, and workspace layout.

Before proposing or implementing any feature, align your decisions with the 
design document’s principles (modular subcommand binaries, Git-native 
workflows, open long-lived formats like UTF-8 CSV with Frictionless Table 
Schema JSON, and transparent auditable operations). If an implementation detail 
is unclear, consult the design document first and follow its conventions rather 
than inventing new ones.

If you discover conflicts between existing code and the design document, do not 
assume either is correct by default. Describe the conflict explicitly (what the 
document says, what the code does, and where the mismatch is). Then propose one 
or more resolution options, including which side to change and why, with the 
impact on users, data formats, compatibility, and module boundaries.

If resolving the conflict requires updating the design document, treat that as 
a first-class outcome: specify the exact wording or section-level edits needed, 
explain the business or technical rationale, and ensure the change remains 
consistent with BusDK’s goals (deterministic behavior, auditable workflows, and 
agent-friendly automation). Only proceed with implementation once the chosen 
resolution is clearly stated and the implied contract is unambiguous.
